snippet.textDisplay: I would never buy a console that doesn't have disk drive unless physically owning games starts working a different way.    But the point is I wouldn't give up physically owning games.   For those curious a great example of why you should do this is minecraft on console.    Basically you may be shocked to know that years back minecraft updated to the better together update and made your old minecraft console edition gone.    That's right now you had an entirely new version of minecraft that wasn't the same at all.   If preferred the old version, but didn't have a physically disk there was no way to get it back.     So I tracked the old version of minecraft for xbox one on e-bay and now I have the legacy console edition of minecraft just how I prefer it.    so yes an entire version of minecraft played by millions was discontinued and you could only get it back with a physical disk.

snippet.textDisplay: The long-term economics is bad for buyers who get the series S console. If you pay $299 this year, you'll need a next-gen console in two years. Accounting for depreciation of pricing, the cost of Xbox X in 2022 will be around $350. So in total, you'll spend about $650 on consoles. Additionally, Xbox consoles need batteries and wouldn't let you play without updating. Thus, bad for countries without unlimited download options their ISPs provide.
snippet.textOriginal: The long-term economics is bad for buyers who get the series S console. If you pay $299 this year, you'll need a next-gen console in two years. Accounting for depreciation of pricing, the cost of Xbox X in 2022 will be around $350. So in total, you'll spend about $650 on consoles.
